title: Part 2
content:
Part 2

MY LIFE IN the White Room had now far exceeded fourteen years, and I reached the age where I would've completed the second-year middle school curriculum in the outside world. The real world outside is different from the virtual one.

However, I found myself adapting to it better than I had imagined. Whether this was due to the curriculum or some other factor was unclear.

As I continued to wait in an empty room following Ishida's instructions, a man approached me.

"Sorry to have kept you waiting, Ayanokouji Kiyotaka-kun. Thank you for coming today."

"Who are you?"

It was a face I had never seen before, a man in his early forties.

He didn't seem like someone involved with the White Room, judging by his gentle appearance.

What caught my eye more was the vase he was holding, which had flowers arranged in it.

This too was something I had never seen before. I had only learned of it and saw such things in images.

"There's a child I desperately want you to meet. I asked Ayanokouji-sensei to allow this."

"I don't understand what you mean."

"That child has become quite weak, and she can't even go out properly. She can only remain calm at home and, to some extent, this clinic. That's why I asked you to come here."

"Is that… sakura?"

"It was just placed in this room for decoration, but I took the liberty of changing the water. It's her favorite flower. She should be returning from her examination soon."

As he spoke, he placed the vase on a shelf by the window.

"Kiyotaka…!"

As I waited with part of the situation still unexplained, the door to the room soon opened, and somebody called out my name.

She seemed to be about my age. The girl was looking at me with wide eyes.

"I've wanted to see you, always… I've always wanted to see you!"

"You're—"

"Yuki, I'm Yuki!"

Yuki. I remembered the name. She was a White Room dropout from a long time ago. Although I had erased her from my memory, it was natural that I still remembered a few things since I couldn't intentionally forget everything.

"Why are you here?"

Even if she hadn't truly died, she had been finished the moment she dropped out.

It was a meeting with the dead. I felt a sense of discomfort, but what was the intention behind this arrangement?

"White… no, ever since she left the same place as you, my daughter Yuki has been weakening. She was shutting herself in. She couldn't go outside and was just continuously worried about you."

The man who spoke and watched from a distance seemed to be Yuki's father.

Her smile was a bit awkward compared to when she was young, but the richness of her emotions was palpable.

"It's really been a long time, hasn't it? Kiyotaka, have you been… in that place all this time?"

She showed a look in her eyes as if she was recalling the past and wore a fearful expression.

From Yuki's and her father's reactions, It seemed there was an aversion to mentioning the White Room's name.

"I've been there for fourteen years. Today is the first time I've come outside."

"You're amazing, Kiyotaka, aren't you… What about the others? Did everyone else get out?"

"I don't know. Everyone was fast to disappear. It's been multiple years since I became the last one."

I hadn't cared about those who had dropped out, including the child in front of me.

"Alone… in that place all this time…? I, I… that, that place…!"

Yuki's body began to tremble, as if her suppressed fear was swelling up.

"Yuki, stop remembering now."

She was digging up memories and becoming distraught. Is a dropout supposed to be this miserable?

The only thing I understood was that this child must've come from a notable, wealthy family.

She had been treated with respect even after dropping out.

However, since she was attending counseling, it seemed her emotional wounds hadn't healed yet.

And one of the healing methods… is for her to meet me, a fellow fourth-generation student, huh…?

I had grasped the situation, and there was no further need for me here.

"I'm leaving now."

"Wait, please! After finally meeting you! I want to talk more, much more!"

"I have nothing to say."

If we couldn't talk about the White Room, then we couldn't have a conversation.

"Please wait, Ayanokouji-kun. Could you please talk with Yuki for a while longer? Any kind of talk will do, even trivial, insignificant matters―"

"What do you mean by insignificant matters? You do understand that today is the first day I've exited into the outside world, right?"

"That's—"

"Of course, if you want, I can make up stories based on whatever knowledge I have, whether it's about Japan or the rest of the world. But that's not what you're hoping for, is it?"

"I-I'm fine. W-With the White Room talk, I'm fine with it, really…"

While hyperventilating, Yuki clung to my sleeve, trying not to let go.

"It's better if you stop. Talking with me is impossible for you."

"No, that's not true… I've always wanted to meet… with you, Kiyotaka…"

"You should've stopped at just that wish. Meeting like this will only make you suffer from the gap between your memories and your ideal. If you want to heal your mind, you should continue treatment here."

That should be enough. Rather than wasting time here, it'd be better to look at the outside scenery.

At least the outside world still holds an opportunity for curiosity to bloom.

"Please, just a little longer—"

Blocking the exit, Yuki's father outstretched his hands to stop me.

"Is that an order?"

"No… that's…"

"It isn't, right? The White Room representative didn't give me any specific instructions."

"Indeed, Ayanokouji-sensei merely promised to let you meet Yuki. It's just a personal request from me."

"Then I refuse."

"Wha―!?"

"I'm refusing because I've judged it to be what's best for her."

"Do you mean to say that you don't care about the children who've dropped out!?"

That's exactly right. The children who've dropped out don't matter.

However, calling me for counseling was this man's mistake.

"If you'll excuse me."

"No! Don't go, Kiyotaka!"

"Nothing has changed since the time you've disappeared."

"…"

"You should be grateful to your parents and focus on your treatment here. The more you expect from me, the more you'll come to regret it."

"No! I want, I want to talk with you, Kiyotaka! More! About what we couldn't talk about back then!"

Her childish tone and reactions hadn't changed since that time years ago.

"Wait! Please!"

"Move aside."

"Yuki… It's not just me who can't get to her. Neither my wife nor my younger daughter's words reach her. They don't reach her at all. However, she talks with you… Do you know how much that could save her…?!"

"Goodbye. It's better if we never meet again. So, if you'll excuse me."

"No! No! Kiyotaka! Noooo!!"

Her crying voice and the adult's voice that couldn't hold back the curses—

Neither reached the depths of my ears. I wasn't interested.

I left the hospital and returned to the car that was waiting nearby.

A person poked their head out of the passenger window and waved.

"H-Hey, Kiyotaka-kun. Is this our first meeting, perhaps? I'm Kamogawa―"

I recognized the face. Even so, I didn't respond and sat down in the empty seat in the back.

"…It's nothing, haha. Can you forget about that?"

After showing a wry smile, he scratched his head and faced forward.

"Let's go."

"As you wish."

From within the car, I quietly focused on viewing the scenery outside the window.

"What do you think about the outside world that you're seeing for the first time?"

"Nothing."

It wasn't that I lacked curiosity.

Just that, at least, no so-called emotion was stirring within me.

"Nothing, huh?"

This man, my father, was probably thinking about it—

That even though I was staring out the window, there were no emotions involved.

That right now, I probably couldn't even distinguish it from the virtual world.

That was a big mistake.

It was just easier to let him think everything was under control.

At least for now, it was beneficial to keep it that way.

There was no need to let this man sense that I was constantly sharpening my fangs.

"You'll continue the White Room's educational curriculum by my side for a while. You'll return to the facility when the White Room resumes."

"Understood."

Even if the environment changes, I won't face any obstacles as long as I have the abilities I've mastered from White Room.
